  "An investor buys 150 shares at $30 each. The stock rises to $37.50 and pays $0.60 in total dividends per share over the holding period. What is the total return in dollars and as a percentage?": "",
  "$1,215 gain (27%)": "",
  "$1,125 gain (22%)": "",
  "$1,125 gain (25%)": "",
  "$1,350 gain (30%)": "",
  "Capital gain = ($37.50 - $30) x 150 = $1,125. Dividends = $0.60 x 150 = $90. Total return = $1,125 + $90 = $1,215. Percentage = $1,215 / ($30 x 150) = $1,215 / $4,500 = 27%.": "",
  "Two stocks both trade at $50. Stock A pays $2.50 annual dividend and its price grows to $55 after one year. Stock B pays no dividend but its price grows to $60. Which stock provided the better total return?": "",
  "Stock B (20% total return) outperformed Stock A (15%)": "",
  "Both had equal returns of 15%": "",
  "Stock A (15% total return) outperformed Stock B (10%)": "",
  "Stock A (20% total return) outperformed Stock B (15%)": "",
  "Stock A: Capital gain = ($55-$50)/$50 = 10%, plus dividend yield = $2.50/$50 = 5%, total return = 15%. Stock B: Capital gain = ($60-$50)/$50 = 20%, no dividend, total return = 20%. Stock B's price appreciation more than compensated for its lack of dividends.": ""
